<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">23349298</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2014</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>31</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2019</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>12</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1543-2742</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>23</Volume><Issue>4</Issue><PubDate><Year>2013</Year><Month>Aug</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>International journal of sport nutrition and exercise metabolism</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Int J Sport Nutr Exerc Metab</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Oral creatine supplementation augments the repeated bout effect.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>378</StartPage><EndPage>387</EndPage><MedlinePgn>378-87</MedlinePgn></Pagination><Abstract><AbstractText Label="PURPOSE" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">We examined the effects of creatine supplementation on the response to repeated bouts of resistance exercise.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">Young men (24.1 &#xb1; 5.2 yr) were divided into Creatine (CM, n = 9) and Placebo (PL, n = 9) groups. On day (D) 1 and D15, subjects performed four sets of bicep curls at 75% 1-RM to concentric failure. On D8-D13, subjects consumed either 20g/d creatine monohydrate or placebo. Muscle soreness and elbow joint range of motion (ROM) were assessed on D1-D5 and D15-D19. Serum creatine kinase activity (CK) was assessed on D1, D3, D5, D15, D17, and D19.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">The first exercise bout produced increases in muscle soreness and CK, and decreases in ROM in both groups (p &lt; .001). The second bout produced lesser rises in serum CK, muscle soreness, and a lesser decrease in ROM (bout effect, p &lt; .01 for all), with greater attenuation of these damage markers in CM than PL. CK levels on D17 were lower (+110% over D15 for CM vs. +343% for PL), muscle soreness from D15-19 was lower (-75% for CM vs. -56% for PL compared with first bout), and elbow ROM was decreased in PL, but not CM on D16 (p &lt; .05 for all).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">Creatine supplementation provides an additive effect on blunting the rise of muscle damage markers following a repeated bout of resistance exercise. The mechanism by which creatine augments the repeated bout effect is unknown but is likely due to a combination of creatine's multifaceted functions.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Veggi K</LastName><ForeName>F T</ForeName><Initials>FT</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Laboratory of Physiology and Biokinetic, Universidade Iguacu, Itaperuna, Brazil.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Machado</LastName><ForeName>Marco</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Koch</LastName><ForeName>Alexander J</ForeName><Initials>AJ</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Santana</LastName><ForeName>Sandro C</ForeName><Initials>SC</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Oliveira</LastName><ForeName>Sedison S</ForeName><Initials>SS</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Stec</LastName><ForeName>Michael J</ForeName><Initials>MJ</Initials></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D016449">Randomized Controlled Trial</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2013</Year><Month>01</Month><Day>23</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>United States</Country><MedlineTA>Int J Sport Nutr Exerc Metab</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>100939812</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>1526-484X</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo><ChemicalList><Chemical><RegistryNumber>EC 2.7.3.2</RegistryNumber><NameOfSubstance UI="D003402">Creatine